TY  - JOUR
T1  - Government Revenue from Inflation
AU  - Friedman, Milton
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259791
DO  - 10.1086/259791
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 846
EP  - 856
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - What rate of inflation will yield the greatest steady state command over real resources to a government having a monopoly on the issue of fiat money? The usual answer--the rate at which the inflation elasticity of demand for real balances is unity--is correct if real income is constant but wrong if real income is rising. The answer then depends also on the growth rate and on the income elasticity of demand for real balances. The revenue-maximizing rate of inflation is generally lower for growing than for constant real income and may even be negative, that is, deflation. Many actual rates of inflation seem higher than the revenue-maximizing rate.
AB  - What rate of inflation will yield the greatest steady state command over real resources to a government having a monopoly on the issue of fiat money? The usual answer--the rate at which the inflation elasticity of demand for real balances is unity--is correct if real income is constant but wrong if real income is rising. The answer then depends also on the growth rate and on the income elasticity of demand for real balances. The revenue-maximizing rate of inflation is generally lower for growing than for constant real income and may even be negative, that is, deflation. Many actual rates of inflation seem higher than the revenue-maximizing rate.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259791
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259791
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Response of Prices and Income to Monetary Policy: An Analysis Based upon a Differential Phillips Curve
AU  - Peterson, David W.
AU  - Lerner, Eugene M.
AU  - Lusk, Edward J.
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259792
DO  - 10.1086/259792
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 857
EP  - 866
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A mathematical model is analyzed to determine the impact of two alternative monetary policies upon the rate of change of prices and the level of real national income. The first is a once and for all change in the rate of growth of the money supply to a new level; the second is found through an optimization analysis using the maximum principle of postaudit. It is found that the second policy not only leads to a final equilibrium position in less time than the first policy, but it also induces less variability in both prices and real income.
AB  - A mathematical model is analyzed to determine the impact of two alternative monetary policies upon the rate of change of prices and the level of real national income. The first is a once and for all change in the rate of growth of the money supply to a new level; the second is found through an optimization analysis using the maximum principle of postaudit. It is found that the second policy not only leads to a final equilibrium position in less time than the first policy, but it also induces less variability in both prices and real income.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259792
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259792
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Reversals of Assumptions and Implications
AU  - De Alessi, Louis
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259793
DO  - 10.1086/259793
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 867
EP  - 877
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The possibility that assumptions and implications may be interchanged has been interpreted by some economists to imply that assumptions can be required to have direct empirical meaning. Such an interpretation is incorrect. Section I summarizes the methodological viewpoint adopted in this essay. Section II contains a discussion of different types of reversals associated with different meanings of assumption. Section III concludes that purported reversals of assumptions and implications do not affect the empirical characteristics of the statements involved and do not cast doubt upon the proposition that the usefulness of economic theory must be judged by the agreement of the theory's logical consequences with observation.
AB  - The possibility that assumptions and implications may be interchanged has been interpreted by some economists to imply that assumptions can be required to have direct empirical meaning. Such an interpretation is incorrect. Section I summarizes the methodological viewpoint adopted in this essay. Section II contains a discussion of different types of reversals associated with different meanings of assumption. Section III concludes that purported reversals of assumptions and implications do not affect the empirical characteristics of the statements involved and do not cast doubt upon the proposition that the usefulness of economic theory must be judged by the agreement of the theory's logical consequences with observation.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259793
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259793
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Productive Efficiency in the Steam-Electric Generating Industry
AU  - Seitz, Wesley D.
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259794
DO  - 10.1086/259794
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 878
EP  - 886
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Linear programming techniques are used to estimate an industry frontier production function. Measures of technical, price, and economic efficiency given scale are calculated. Analyses of these indexes indicate that both neutral and nonneutral economies of scale exist, nonneutral (fuel saving) technological advance has occurred, and plant efficiency is related to the production technique utilized. These results are interpreted to imply that the frontier function and the multidimensional efficiency indexes are reasonable. The possibility is raised that reliance on the fuel conversion ratio as a measure of plant efficiency has resulted in nonoptimum combinations of factors.
AB  - Linear programming techniques are used to estimate an industry frontier production function. Measures of technical, price, and economic efficiency given scale are calculated. Analyses of these indexes indicate that both neutral and nonneutral economies of scale exist, nonneutral (fuel saving) technological advance has occurred, and plant efficiency is related to the production technique utilized. These results are interpreted to imply that the frontier function and the multidimensional efficiency indexes are reasonable. The possibility is raised that reliance on the fuel conversion ratio as a measure of plant efficiency has resulted in nonoptimum combinations of factors.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259794
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259794
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Resource Allocation in Traditional Agriculture: Republican China, 1937-1940
AU  - Dittrich, Scott R.
AU  - Myers, Ramon H.
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259795
DO  - 10.1086/259795
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 887
EP  - 896
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This essay discusses and measures the efficiency of resource allocation by peasants in three villages located in the grain-producing area of north China between 1937 and 1940. Family farm budget data collected by Japanese researchers were used to determine how well peasants allocated their land and labor between four major grain crops. Marginal value products for land and labor were obtained from fitting data to a Cobb-Douglas production function for each grain crop. These values were then equalized by the method of iteration and substituted in the original production function to obtain the maximum income obtainable had peasants allocated their resources with maximum efficiency. When peasant farm income was compared with the maximum income obtainable, the results showed that in spite of increasing market uncertainty, peasants were allocating their land and labor very efficiently.
AB  - This essay discusses and measures the efficiency of resource allocation by peasants in three villages located in the grain-producing area of north China between 1937 and 1940. Family farm budget data collected by Japanese researchers were used to determine how well peasants allocated their land and labor between four major grain crops. Marginal value products for land and labor were obtained from fitting data to a Cobb-Douglas production function for each grain crop. These values were then equalized by the method of iteration and substituted in the original production function to obtain the maximum income obtainable had peasants allocated their resources with maximum efficiency. When peasant farm income was compared with the maximum income obtainable, the results showed that in spite of increasing market uncertainty, peasants were allocating their land and labor very efficiently.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259795
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259795
Y2  - 2024/03/22
