TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Neolithic Agricultural Revolution and the Origins of Private Property
AU  - Bowles, Samuel
AU  - Choi, Jung-Kyoo
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701789
DO  - 10.1086/701789
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2186
EP  - 2228
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
AB  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701789
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701789
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Using a Probabilistic Frontier Production Function to Measure Technical Efficiency
AU  - Timmer, C. P.
Y1  - 1971/07/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259787
DO  - 10.1086/259787
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 776
EP  - 794
VL  - 79
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This article uses linear programming techniques to "estimate" a frontier Cobb-Douglas production function for U.S. agriculture from 1960 to 1967, using the "average farm" in each state in each year as an observation. Both deterministic and probabilistic frontiers are generated and the results compared with ordinary least-squares and analysis of covariance estimates of the production function. Technical inefficiency is defined relative to the probabilistic frontier function and the extent of any inefficiency calculated for each state. Little technical inefficiency exists across states when the production function includes intermediate inputs as well as land, labor, and capital.
AB  - This article uses linear programming techniques to "estimate" a frontier Cobb-Douglas production function for U.S. agriculture from 1960 to 1967, using the "average farm" in each state in each year as an observation. Both deterministic and probabilistic frontiers are generated and the results compared with ordinary least-squares and analysis of covariance estimates of the production function. Technical inefficiency is defined relative to the probabilistic frontier function and the extent of any inefficiency calculated for each state. Little technical inefficiency exists across states when the production function includes intermediate inputs as well as land, labor, and capital.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259787
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259787
Y2  - 2024/03/22
